result.execSummary:
The defendant John O Huff was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft-Movable Property <=$2500, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Case called at 3:50pm [mo]
Defendant John O Huff in court with Attorney Whitney Hagemann.   ADA Jeffrey Shock appears for the State of Wisconsin.
ADA Shock submits a victim impact statement
Mr. Podevels addresses the Court

Counsel makes sentencing arguments
Counsel agree on amount of restitution owed
The Court finds that Mr. Huff is able to pay the restitution amount over the course of probation 

On Count #1, the Court withholds sentence, and places Defendant on Probation for 1 year, with conditions:

--to serve 10 days in the Jeffeson County Jail, with Huber privliges, to commence 5/27/16 any time before 7:00pm 
--the Court authorizes transfer of sentence to another county so long as it is served without passive confinement and at no additional cost to Jefferson County. 

--to pay restitution in the amount of $1,550 to Michael J. Podevels
--Mr. Huff is only to work in home improvement industry with approval of agent
--If, Mr. Huff is to work as a contractor he must disclose this conviction to potential client
--to pay statutory costs
--the Court encourages the DOC to set an agressive timetable for repayment

The Court does not order a DNA sample
The Court allows Mr. Huff to report to probation tomorrow due to the late hour.
